haped the manner by which LGBT Singaporeans are framing and subsequently claiming rights. Phillips argues that the activism engaged in by LGBT Singaporeans for governmental and societal recognition is in many respects virtual. His analysis documents how the actions of activists have resulted in some noteworthy changes in the lives of LGBT Singaporeans, but nothing as grand as some would have hoped, thus indexing the "not quite" aspect of the virtual. Yet, Virtual Activism also demonstrates how these actions have encouraged LGBT Singaporeans to fight even harder for their rights, signalling the "possibilities" that the virtual holds.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aGay activistszSingaporevCase studies. 0aGay liberation movementzSingaporevCase studies. 0aGay rightszSingaporevCase studies. 0aHomophobiazSingaporevCase studies. 0aInternetxSocial aspectszSingaporevCase studies. 0aSexual minoritieszSingaporevCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aAsia.  aLGBTQ.  aSingapore.  aactivism.  aethnography.  ainternet.  amovements.  aqueer.  asexuality.  asocial.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069045340uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753627540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487536275423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487536275.jpg  a978-3-11-069045-3  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles